Similar to both Unreal World and Dwarf Fortress, Engi needs both a travel map and a local map. The local map is where most of the game takes place, the travel map is used to quickly get from Point A to Point B. The local map must be a 1:1 scale of Japan using historical sources, archeological sources, and satellite maps to make the map as accurate as possible. Each tile represents a 1 meter squared. To cut down on game space and system resources, a combination of hand-crafted points of interest alongside procedural generation must be employed. All important cities, temples, and natural wonders must be hand-crafted as accurately as possible while keeping the 1:1 scale. I also want to employ Z-Levels, similar to Dwarf Fortress, so a player can look above and below them. Each building, tree, hill and mountain must be accurately represented to scale. However, minor towns, caves, and wilderness can be procedurally generated (except the names of these environments, they must be accurate to the area they represent). These environments once explored must remain static, so if the player returns they will be exactly the same. On the travel map, a player can travel from one side of Japan to another, however because of the huge scale, that would take so long, but I still want it to be possible. I also want the ability for a person to reach hand-crafted points of interest if they start from the wilderness, but finding roads and reading signs. Please consider historical evidence of waystations, inns, and anything that a traveler would have discovered during the mid 1500’s. Each clan must be represented.